US ATLAS Software Nightly Code Browser
acode-browser1.usatlas.bnl.gov server
 

Facts

  • LXR indexer is available for browsing of ATLAS code
  • NEW: GeoModel code is added
  • The Code-Browsing cluster at the U.S. ATLAS Tier 1 Facility includes two servers:
    1. Nightly releases server acode-browser1.usatlas.bnl.gov
      • Alias of the nightly server acode-browser.usatlas.bnl.gov (in the past it was the address of the old server that is no longer available)
    2. Stable releases server acode-browser2.usatlas.bnl.gov
  • The main feature of LXR indexer is the ability to jump easily to the declaration of any global identifier. Even all references to global identifiers are indexed. The indexes are stored in the MySQL database
  • LXR provides free-text search via Ripgrep, which supports regular expressions

Nightly Release

US ATLAS Software Code Browsing
acode-browser2.usatlas.bnl.gov stable releases server
 

Facts

  • LXR indexer is available for browsing of ATLAS code
  • This is the US ATLAS service primarily for US ATLAS members. However, all ATLAS developers can use it
  • The Code-Browsing cluster at the U.S. ATLAS Tier 1 Facility includes two servers:
    1. nightly releases server acode-browser1.usatlas.bnl.gov
    2. stable releases server acode-browser2.usatlas.bnl.gov
  • The main feature of LXR indexer is the ability to jump easily to the declaration of any global identifier. Even all references to global identifiers are indexed. The indexes are stored in the MySQL database
  • LXR provides free-text search via Ripgrep, which supports regular expressions

Stable Releases Server

Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment

 

 

About the experiment

  • The Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment is a neutrino-oscillation experiment designed to measure the mixing angle q13  using anti-neutrinos produced by the reactors of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant (NPP) and the Ling Ao NPP.

Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment

 

 

About the experiment

  • The Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment is a neutrino-oscillation experiment designed to measure the mixing angle q13  using anti-neutrinos produced by the reactors of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant (NPP) and the Ling Ao NPP.

Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment

 

 

About the experiment

  • The Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment is a neutrino-oscillation experiment designed to measure the mixing angle q13  using anti-neutrinos produced by the reactors of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant (NPP) and the Ling Ao NPP.

About the experiment

The Daya Bay Neutrino Experiment is a neutrino-oscillation experiment designed to measure the mixing angle q13  using anti-neutrinos produced by the reactors of the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant (NPP) and the Ling Ao NPP.

1. Motivation

Recent discoveries have shown that neutrinos are massive. Mixing among the mass states has been observed in atmospheric and solar neutrinos in experiments such as Super-K and SNO as well as in experiments using man-made neutrino sources including KamLAND and K2K. In the neutrino mixing matrix, all but two parameters have been measured: the smallest mixing angle, q13, and the value of the CP violating phase, dCP, are not yet known. To date, the most sensitive limit on q13 is sin22q13<0.17 for Dm213 = 2.5r10-3 eV2 which was reported by the CHOOZ reactor anti-neutrino disappearance experiment with a baseline of 1.05 km.

Reactor anti-neutrino experiments have played a critical role in the 50-year-long history of neutrinos, from the discovery of the anti-neutrino by Reines and Cowan to the first observation of reactor anti-neutrino disappearance at KamLAND. Supernovas: Making Astronomical History

Supernovas, the glamorous death throes of massive stars, have pushed scientific knowledge further and further into the unknown for thousands of years. Our current project, SNEWS, is only the most recent chapter in a very long story.

SNEWS:
Un sistema di allarme immediato da supernova

Nel mondo esistono diversi rivelatori, attualmente in funzione o in fase di completamento, sensibili ai neutrini provenienti da una supernova da collasso gravitazionale nella nostra Galassia. Il segnale neutrinico fuoriesce immediatamente dal nucleo della supernova, mentre occorrono alcune ore perchè i primi fotoni diventino visibili. La rivelazione dei neutrini correlati a una supernova nella nostra Galassia rappresenta dunque un allarme immediato (early warning) per gli astronomi. Facendo lavorare diversi rivelatori in coincidenza è possibile informare in modo decisamente affidabile la comunità astronomica quando si verifica una supernova. Inoltre l'allarme diffuso da SNEWS può servire ad attivare dei rivelatori che, da soli, non sarebbero in grado di identificare il segnale neutrinico, consentendo dunque di registrare più dati.

Il progetto SNEWS è una collaborazione di rappresentanti degli attuali rivelatori di neutrini da supernova. Saranno inoltre coinvolti i rivelatori di onde gravitazionali. L'obiettivo di SNEWS è di fornire un allarme immediato alla comunità astronomica in occasione di un collasso gravitazionale nella nostra Galassia. La collaborazione è anche impegnata in lavori cooperativi tra i vari esperimenti, come il coordinamento dei periodi di inattività

Alrededor del mundo, varios detectores actualmente en funcionamiento o a punto de ser finalizados son sensibles a la señal de neutrinos producida por el colapso del núcleo de una supernova en la Vía Láctea. Broad RAnge Hadron Magnetic Spectrometers Experiment at RHIC

The BRAHMS experiment was designed to measure charged hadrons over a wide range of rapidity and transverse momentum to study the reaction mechanisms of the relativistic heavy ion reactions at RHIC (Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider at Brookhaven National Laboratory) and the properities of the highly excited nuclear matter formed in these reaction. The experimet took its first data during the RHIC 2000 year run and completed datataking in June 2006. Results in form of publications, public presentatitons can be found under the public results.

STAR Code of Conduct


The STAR Collaboration believes that our scientific mission is best achieved by building a culture of inclusion, integrity and cooperation that affords all members the opportunity to reach their full potential. All STAR collaborators commit to a high level of professional behavior, to fostering a harassment and bullying-free environment and to actively countering instances of unprofessional behavior. We pledge to respond to criticism respectfully and will strive to model behaviors that encourage productive debate and disagreement, both within our communities and where we are criticized. STAR collaborators will extend this level of respect and professional discourse to those outside our collaboration and the broader scientific community as well.

Inappropriate actions or statements by collaboration members that are derogatory or defamatory on the basis of identity, including but not limited to: age, race, ethnicity, sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, marital status, nationality, political affiliation, disability, educational and/or socioeconomic background, neurodiversity, mental or physical health, or any other characteristic protected by law, will not be tolerated. Disruptive or harassing behavior of any kind will not be tolerated. Harassment includes but is not limited to inappropriate or intimidating behavior and language, unwelcome jokes or comments, unwanted touching or attention, offensive images, photography without permission, bullying, and stalking.
